\begin_layout Standard
This can be proven the following way.
 We know the grassman gaussian integral 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int{\cal D}[c^{\dagger},c]e^{-c_{u}^{+}A_{uv}c_{v}}=\det\mathbf{A}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

So we can use this 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\delta}{\delta A_{ij}}\det\mathbf{A} & = & \frac{\delta}{\delta A_{ij}}\int{\cal D}[c^{\dagger},c]e^{-c_{u}^{+}A_{uv}c_{v}}\\
 & = & \int{\cal D}[c^{\dagger},c](-c_{i}^{+}c_{j})e^{-c_{u}^{+}A_{uv}c_{v}}\\
 & = & -\det\mathbf{A}\langle c_{i}^{+}c_{j}\rangle
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the average is taken with respect to the action 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=c_{u}^{+}A_{uv}c_{v}
\]

\end_inset

and is by definition the bare propagator 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal G}_{ji}=\langle c_{i}^{+}c_{j}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 However, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal G}=-\mathbf{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\delta}{\delta A_{ij}}\det\mathbf{A} & = & [\mathbf{A}^{-1}]_{ji}\,\det\mathbf{A}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

